<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="231" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,613,926]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,613,638]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Male (
<figureCitation box="[358,460,613,638]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1921,1943]" captionTargetBox="[150,1424,691,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[150,1436,690,1900]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 18. Ptilothyris loxocasis Meyrick (18A–E) and Ptilothyris nausicaa Meyrick (18F). A, Lectotype, male, in RMCA; B, Labels of lectotype; C, Male genitalia, gen. slide no. CIS-7221, with a close-up of uncus and of juxta; D, Phallus, with a close-up of cornutus; E, Abdomen; F, P. nausicaa, holotype, male, in NHMUK." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2594895/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">Fig. 18F</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyr. E, Meyrick" authorityYear="1926" box="[484,713,613,638]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nausicaa">
<emphasis box="[484,713,613,638]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">Ptilothyris nausicaa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is superficially similar to the 
<emphasis box="[1065,1175,613,638]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">Thubdora</emphasis>
species in having less elongate forewing with rounded outer margin. On the other hand, the antenna of this species is dark purple basally and matches well with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walsingham" authorityYear="1897" box="[411,529,685,710]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[411,529,685,710]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">Ptilothyris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The antennae of the 
<typeStatus box="[774,872,685,710]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">holotype</typeStatus>
are both broken beyond middle, but, according to the original description, the apical third is white.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
